Loan Data Exploration¶

by Lavish Lalwani¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a loan dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. It will focus the analysis on around 10 variables.

Dataset Structure¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features. Most variables are numeric or dates in nature, but some are texts like occupation and employment status.

Main Feature of Interest¶

For this exploration, I will look into the borrower annual percentage rate (BorrowerAPR). I want to learn about what features in the dataset influences this rate.

Features to Support the Investigation¶

I feel that the main determining factor of the borrower APR is the borrower's employment details. As such, I will look into EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, IncomeRange and IncomeVerifiable closely. I'll also expand my exploration to some other features like OpenCreditLines, CurrentCreditLines, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, and LoanOriginalAmount.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I'll look into the distributions of each individual features. Let's start with the feature of interest and then move to most interesting employment related ones in this order: EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, IncomeRange and IncomeVerifiable.

Univariate Exploration Summary¶

The distribution of the main variable of interest (Borrower APR) was loosely binomial, however, there was an interesting spike in the data at approximately 0.35%. Most of the distributions were right skewed.

Some of the features in the dataset had unusual points. For example, there are people earning 0 dollars and being employed for many months. Also, there were people with an income duration of 0 months but have verified employment. These outliers were removed for safety.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, we will look at relationships between variables explored in the last section. To start, we will check the variables for any correlations.

In [203]:
numeric_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'EmploymentStatusDuration', 'OpenCreditLines', 
                'CreditScoreRangeMean', 'LoanOriginalAmount']
categoric_vars = ['IncomeVerifiable', 'IncomeRange', 'EmploymentStatus', 'IsBorrowerHomeowner']
In [204]:
# create a correlation plot

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
sb.heatmap(loans[numeric_vars].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f', cmap = 'vlag_r')
plt.show()

Looking at the heatmap above, interestingly, there's not a lot of variables correlating with BorrowerAPR. We'll now look at the plots to be sure.

In [206]:
# plot matrix of sample of 1000 loans

samples = np.random.choice(loans.shape[0], 1000, replace = False)
loans_samp = loans.loc[samples,:]

g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_samp, vars = numeric_vars);
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20);
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

Looking at the matrix above shows that of the numeric data being analysed, BorrowerAPR is not strongly correlated with any variables. It does have a negative correlation with the Credit Score. Although, this is not a strong negative correlation. BorrowerAPR seems to also be lower for bigger loan amounts. This is presumably to avoid it costing the borrower too much. There is also a positive correlation between loan amount and credit score, showing that larger loans are usually only given when the credit scores are higher.

I will explore the relationship between BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeMean and between BorrowerAPR and LoanOriginalAmount further as it shows a bit of correlation.

In [219]:
# Produce a scatter plot between BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeMean

plt.figure(figsize = [8, 6])
plt.scatter(data = loans, x = 'CreditScoreRangeMean', y = 'BorrowerAPR', alpha = 0.05)
plt.xlabel('Credit Score')
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR')
plt.show()

This is quite interesting. Loans are being given out at all ranges of credit score. However, lower credit scores tend to attract a higher Borrower APR. Although, not strong, there is clearly a negative correlation between BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeMean.

Now, let's look at the relationship between BorrowerAPR and LoanOriginalAmount further below.

In [225]:
# Produce a scatter plot between BorrowerAPR and LoanOriginalAmount

We see from the above plot that generally the higher the loan amount, the more BorrowerAPR is distributed in the lower range (more focused).

Now, let's look at how BorrowerAPR relate to the categorical variables first.

In [208]:
# Plot categorical variables with Borrower APR and Credit Score

fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols = 1, nrows = 4 , figsize = [15,20])

for i in range(len(categoric_vars)):
    var = categoric_vars[i]
    sb.violinplot(data = loans, x = var, y = 'BorrowerAPR', ax = ax[i], color = default_color)

plt.show()

Looking at the violin plots above, there are some interesting insights.

  • Looking at the distributions for the 2 IncomeVerifiable categories, we can see that loans which has a verified income generally have a lower BorrowerAPR. Vice versa, those loans with incomes not verified mainly fall in the ranges of higher BorrowerAPR.
  • Income range seems to have a clear impact on BorrowerAPR as well. The lower the income, the more loans we see have a higher BorrowerAPR.
  • Looking at EmploymentStatus and BorrowerAPR shows that those are not employed have a higher BorrowerAPR. It is interesting to see that loans with part time employment has a similar BorrowerAPR distribution to full time employment.
  • Being a home loan owner doesn't seem to effect BorrowerAPR too much.

Now, let's look at how the 4 categorical vairbales relate to each other.

Bivariate Exploration Summary¶

Many interesting relationships was uncovered in this section. Some of the ones with the main feature of interest, the BorrowerAPR are as per below:

  • BorrowerAPR is negatively correlated with credit score.
  • BorrowerAPR is negatively correlated with loan amount.
  • The income range has a clear effect on BorrowerAPR with higher income ranges having lower BorrowerAPR.
  • Whether or not the income could be verified has a clear effect on BorrowerAPR with verified incomes having much lower BorrowerAPR.
  • Employment status influences BorrowerAPR with more stable employment having lower overall BorrowerAPR.
  • It was interesting that the open credit lines, employment duration and home loan status didn't effect BorrowerAPR much.

There were also some relationships between other features as per below:

  • Home loan owners tend to fall in higher income ranges. This may be why having a home loan did not effect the BorrowerAPR as much as I thought it would.
  • Loans with higher income are generally employed full time and self-employed.
  • There is a positive correlation between loan amount and credit score.

Multivariate Exploration¶

For this section, I'm most interested in looking multivariate relationships between variables we know has an effect on BorrowerAPR from the last section. These variables are: Credit Score, Loan Amount, Income Range, Income Verifiability and Employment Status. Now, because the Employment Status data we have is not very clear, we will ignore that one.

I'm most interested in the following relationships:

  • Relationship between BorrowerAPR, credit score and income verifiability. E.g. If someone with a not verifiable income has a high credit rating, does it effect their BorrowerAPR?
  • Relationship between BorrowerAPR, income range and loan amount. E.g. If someone within a lower income range asks for a bigger loan, does that reduce their BorrowerAPR?
  • Relationship between BorrowerAPR, credit score and loan amount. E.g. Does the loan amount effects someone's BorrowerAPR if their credit score is low/high?
  • Relationship between BorrowerAPR, income range and income verifiability. E.g. Does a loan with a high supporting income but not verifiable get a higher BorrowerAPR?

First, let's look at the relationship between BorrowerAPR, credit score and income verifiability.

In [257]:
# Plot the relationship between BorrowerAPR, credit score and income verifiability.

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loans, col = 'IncomeVerifiable', size = 6);
g.map(plt.scatter, 'CreditScoreRangeMean', 'BorrowerAPR', alpha = 0.1);

Looking at the plot above, we can see that:

  • Not many loans are given where the credit score is lower and income is not verifiable.
  • Generally speaking, if the income is not verifiable, a higher credit score is required to get the same BorrowerAPR compared to when the income is verified.

Now, let's look at the relationship between BorrowerAPR, income range and loan amount.

In [260]:

Looking at the plot above, we can see that generally larger loans are not given out to people with lower income. The relationship between BorrowerAPR and Loan Amount doesn't seem to be impacted by Income Range.

In [284]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loans, col = 'IncomeVerifiable', row = 'IncomeRange', size = 4,

plt.ylim(0, 500);

Looking at the plot above, we see that the distribution of BorrowerAPR changes with different income ranges. If the income is verifiable, the higher the income range, the more the distribution becomes right skewed and vice versa. If the income is not verifiable, it seems the distribution always remains left skewed. This shows that the BorrowerAPR is generally always higher when the income is not verifiable.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Multivariate Exploration Summary¶

From the exploration in this section, I found that:

  • If the income is not verifiable, a higher credit score is required to get the same BorrowerAPR compared to when the income is verified.
  • The income range can effect the loan amount. Lower income ranges do not usually have larger loans.
  • The loan amount and credit score variables strengthened each other. They are both negatively correlated with BorrowerAPR.
  • Income verifiability is very important to not get a high BorrowerAPR. Regardless of other variables, if income is not verifiable, it significantly increases BorrowerAPR.
